---
import GetStartedLayout from "../../layouts/GetStartedLayout.astro";
---

<GetStartedLayout
  title="FAQs"
  current="faq"
  description="Frequently asked questions about Prism, tokens, themes, and contributing."
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <h1 data-i18n="getStarted.toc.faq">FAQs</h1>
    <p class="intro" data-i18n="getStarted.faq.intro">
      Common questions from designers, engineers, and partners onboarding to Prism.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary data-i18n="getStarted.faq.q1">What is Prism?</summary>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.faq.a1">
          Prism is our design system for web: semantic tokens, documented UI patterns, and a component
          library that keeps design files and production code speaking the same language.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary data-i18n="getStarted.faq.q2">How is this page different from the home page?</summary>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.faq.a2">
          Home is a fast orientation—what Prism is and where to go next. Get started splits overview, mission,
          principles, language, and FAQs into separate pages so you can internalize how decisions are made
          before you open foundations or components.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary data-i18n="getStarted.faq.q3">Where should designers start? What about engineers?</summary>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.faq.a3">
          Designers usually begin with foundations and Figma libraries, then map work to documented
          patterns. Engineers start from tokens and components in code, using the reference app for props and
          behavior. Both paths converge on the same semantic roles.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary data-i18n="getStarted.faq.q4">How do tokens connect Figma and code?</summary>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.faq.a4">
          Tokens name intent (for example, “text secondary” or “border strong”). Figma variables and CSS
          custom properties both resolve from that contract, so when a token updates, design and
          implementation move together.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary data-i18n="getStarted.faq.q5">How do I propose a new component or pattern?</summary>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.faq.a5">
          Open a short proposal with the user problem, at least two product touchpoints, and accessibility
          notes. One-off visuals can stay local; repeated flows with shared risk belong in Prism after
          review.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary data-i18n="getStarted.faq.q6">How do themes work in documentation and in product?</summary>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.faq.a6">
          Themes swap the values behind semantic tokens while structure stays fixed. Use the header theme
          picker here to preview palettes; in application code, always bind to semantic roles—not raw
          hex—so theme changes remain safe.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <p class="next">
    <a class="next-link" href="/foundations/color" data-i18n="getStarted.nextFoundations">
      Continue to color foundations
    </a>
  </p>
</GetStartedLayout>
